I&#039;d be willing to break away from desktop PCs altogether were it not for two advantages still enjoyed over laptops: ease of parts replacement and mutli-monitor support. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If my laptop mobo dies, I&#039;m in for a lengthy and expensive replacement process (assuming it&#039;s not cheaper to junk it). With a desktop, I order a replacement from Newegg and three days later I&#039;m back in business. Also, desktop video cards routinely have two video out ports, whereas laptops need extra hardware (docks, dongles, etc.) to add a second monitor and the process is often cumbersome. &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Until laptops can close these two gaps, I don&#039;t think desktop PCs can die off altogether, but you&#039;re right -- their advantages versus laptops are dwindling.
